&gt; Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; &gt; Neil,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Thank you for the example. Would it be sufficient to make
&gt; &gt; invokeTestMethod(Method method) protected so you could subclass
&gt; &gt; TestClassRunner?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;   
&gt; &gt;&gt; From: junit@yahoogroups.com [mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com] On 
&gt; &gt;&gt; Behalf Of Neil Swingler
&gt; &gt;&gt;     
&gt; &gt;&gt; decorating a test class TestSuite in JUnit3 but does not offer a 
&gt; &gt;&gt; solution to decorating the individual test methods.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; Lets say I code a custom Runner to run each test in it&#39;s own 
&gt; &gt;&gt; classloader 
&gt; &gt;&gt; but otherwise I want all the other standard JUnit4 
&gt; annotations to be 
&gt; &gt;&gt; respected. I can reuse the TestIntrospector and 
&gt; &gt;&gt; TestMethodRunner classes 
&gt; &gt;&gt; (although they are in an internal package). But there is 
&gt; &gt;&gt; still code in 
&gt; &gt;&gt; TestClassRunner to do with exception handling that I will 
&gt; &gt;&gt; have to duplicate.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;     
&gt; Hi Kent, I have made invokeTestMethod protected in my version 
&gt; of junit. 
&gt; It enables me to introduce the classloader. Here is my code:
&gt; 
&gt; public class ReloadingTestClassRunner extends TestClassRunner {
&gt;     private TestNotifier notifier;
&gt;     private Class&lt;?&gt; testClass;
&gt; 
&gt;     public void initialize(TestNotifier notifier,
&gt;             Class&lt;? extends Object&gt; testClass) {
&gt;         super.initialize(notifier, testClass);
&gt;         this.notifier = notifier;
&gt;         this.testClass = testClass;
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     protected void invokeTestMethod(Method method) throws Exception {
&gt;         ClassReloader classReloader = new ClassReloader(
&gt;                 (URLClassLoader) testClass
&gt;                         .getClassLoader());
&gt;         Class&lt;?&gt; reloadedClass = classReloader
&gt;                 .reload(testClass);
&gt;         Method reloadedMethod = reloadedClass.getMethod(method
&gt;                 .getName(), (Class[]) method
&gt;                 .getParameterTypes());
&gt;         new TestMethodRunner(reloadedClass.newInstance(),
&gt;                 reloadedMethod, this.notifier).run();
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; - Neil
